[1] China - Newswire
Date: 14 Dec 2011
Source: Shanghai Daily / Xinhua [edited]
http://www.shanghaidaily.com/article/article_xinhua.asp?id=38947


Polio cases reach 20 in Xinjiang
--------------------
The number of polio cases recorded in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region since an outbreak was confirmed in August [2011] has
reached 20, local health officials said Wednesday [14 Dec 2011].

The Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention had been testing
samples taken from patients in the region diagnosed with Acute Flaccid
Paralysis (AFP), a common indicator of polio, to check for the
disease. On [5 Dec 2011], the tests uncovered 2 new polio cases, said
the officials.

One of the samples was taken from a 53-year-old patient from Aksu
prefecture who died on [23 Oct 2011], taking the confirmed number of
deaths from polio in the Xinjiang outbreak to 2.

Poliomyelitis, or polio, is a viral disease of the brain and spinal
cord that mainly affects children under five years of age. One in 200
infections leads to irreversible paralysis, usually in the legs.

AFP is a sudden onset of weakness or paralysis, as is commonly found
with polio.

Local health officials said the 1st 3 cases of this year's [2011]
polio outbreak came from abroad [The virus was identified as
genetically similar to those currently circulating in neighboring
Pakistan. See prior ProMED-mail post Poliomyelitis - worldwide (11):
China 20110827.2625 for more information. - Mod.MPP]

Xinjiang neighbors 3 of the 4 polio-endemic countries in the world:
Afghanistan, India, Nigeria and Pakistan (for a map showing the
proximity of Afghanistan, India and Pakistan to Xinjian, see
http://www.sacu.org/maps/provmap.png. - Mod.MPP]

The local government has conducted large-scale vaccinations in
response to the region's polio epidemic that started in August, when
the 1st cases of the disease in China since 2000 were discovered.

Health authorities said 4 regions in Xinjiang -- the prefectures of
Hotan, Kashgar, Bayingolin and Aksu -- were classified as epidemic
zones.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[See below official note from the Polio Eradication Initiative (in
section [3]) on these newly confirmed cases. The most recent date of
onset of these cases is 9 Oct 2011. Prior to these new cases, the
most recent date of onset of confirmed cases was on 18 Sep 2011. It
appears as though there is a delay in confirmation of cases so it may
be too early to conclude that transmission of the Wild poliovirus
(WPV) has been interrupted.

For the interactive HealthMap/ProMED map of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, see http://healthmap.org/r/1aQE. - Mod.MPP]

