[2] Pakistan - Newswire
Date: 15 Dec 2011
Source: Central Asia Online [edited]
http:
//centralasiaonline.com/en_GB/articles/caii/newsbriefs/2011/12/15/newsbrief-11

Health workers have recorded 6 new polio cases in Pakistan, bringing
the number of polio-infected children to 173 so far this year [2011],
officials said [15 Dec 2011].

Doctors found 4 new cases in Balochistan and one each in Khyber
Pakhtunkhwa and Frontier Region Kohat, Dr. Altaf Bosan, head of the
prime minister’s Polio Eradication Cell, told Central Asia Online.

Pakistan is the biggest contributor to the world’s 565 polio cases
reported so far in 2011, he said.

Media reports have linked the number of polio cases to a campaign by
the Taliban to prevent parents from getting immunisations for their
children. The Taliban claim that polio vaccines are a conspiracy by
the West to sterilise Muslims, thus reducing the Muslim population.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As mentioned in a prior ProMED-mail post (Poliomyelitis - worldwide
(18): Pakistan, global 20111208.3552), the mention of a smear campaign
on the part of fundamentalists in Pakistan is a deju vu of what
happened in northern Nigeria in 2003/2004 which was responsible for
reintroduction of wild poliovirus (WPV) into many countries which had
previously interrupted transmission of WPV.

For the interactive HealthMap/ProMED map of Pakistan, see
http://healthmap.org/r/1iGJ - Mod.MPP]

